{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17520412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17520412"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:23:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:23:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13191"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13191","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13191"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.07,0.77,0.04,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5627"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106097"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5627","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5627"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13191"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88572"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1919"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9595"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10381"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37181"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44297"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106097"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of lethargy and increasing shortness of breath. She reports repeated episodes of sore throat with low-grade fever. Two days ago, she experienced a nosebleed that initially stopped with pinching but later continued to ooze intermittently. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears pale with petechial rashes on both arms and legs. Her pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 118/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 38.0\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 65 g/L (115-155)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 0.5 \u00d7 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (4.0-10.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMean corpuscular volume: 89 fL (80-96)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMean corpuscular haemoglobin: 31 pg (26-32)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets: 5 \u00d7 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EReticulocyte count: 0.05% (0.6-2.5%)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum creatinine: 80 \u03bcmol/L (60-110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood film: unremarkable\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most appropriate to confirm the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Peripheral blood flow cytometry","Serum protein electrophoresis","Bone marrow biopsy","Haemoglobin electrophoresis","Fluorescence in situ hybridisation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with pancytopenia (anaemia, neutropenia, and thrombocytopenia), a low reticulocyte count, and a bland blood film showing reduced numbers of all cell types. These findings are characteristic of bone marrow failure, specifically aplastic anaemia. The most important next step is \u003Cstrong\u003Ebone marrow biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E, which will show a hypocellular marrow with increased fat spaces and loss of haematopoietic precursors, confirming the diagnosis and excluding other causes of pancytopenia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum protein electrophoresis\u003C/strong\u003E is used to detect monoclonal proteins in conditions such as multiple myeloma or other plasma cell disorders. While myeloma can cause anaemia, it typically presents with other features such as hypercalcaemia, renal impairment, or bone lesions. Presentation with pancytopenia is possible but less common.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeripheral blood flow cytometry\u003C/strong\u003E is useful for identifying abnormal cell populations in leukaemias and lymphomas. However, the bland blood film with reduced cell numbers rather than abnormal cells makes a haematological malignancy less likely as the primary diagnosis. Of note, testing for paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria may support the diagnosis of aplastic anaemia if a clone is found. However, confirmation of the diagnosis requires a bone marrow biopsy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemoglobin electrophoresis\u003C/strong\u003E is used to diagnose haemoglobinopathies such as thalassaemia or sickle cell disease. These conditions do not cause pancytopenia and would typically present with specific red cell morphology changes on the blood film.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluorescence in situ hybridisation\u003C/strong\u003E (FISH) is a cytogenetic technique used to detect specific chromosomal abnormalities in haematological malignancies, for example \u003Cem\u003EBCR::ABL1 \u003C/em\u003Ein chronic myeloid leukaemia, \u003Cem\u003EPML::RARA\u003C/em\u003E in acute promyelocytic leukaemia. These diagnoses are unlikely based on the investigations shown.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of pancytopenia with a low reticulocyte count and bland blood film strongly suggests bone marrow failure. Bone marrow biopsy is essential to distinguish aplastic anaemia from other causes of pancytopenia such as myelodysplastic syndrome, acute leukaemia, or marrow infiltration.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Aplastic anaemia presents with pancytopenia and a low reticulocyte count.","Bone marrow biopsy is required to confirm the diagnosis of aplastic anaemia and assess marrow cellularity."],"references":["DeZern AE, Churpek JE. Approach to the diagnosis of aplastic anemia. Blood Adv. 2021 Jun 22;5(12):2660-2671. doi: 10.1182/bloodadvances.2021004345. PMID: 34156438; PMCID: PMC8270669.","Giudice V, Selleri C. Aplastic anemia: Pathophysiology. Semin Hematol. 2022 Jan;59(1):13-20. doi: 10.1053/j.seminhematol.2021.12.002. Epub 2022 Jan 5. PMID: 35491054."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88572"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13191"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88572","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88572"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-15T21:11:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-15T21:13:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5627"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106097"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"at